December 4, 2012
The U.S. warned Syria against chemical weapons. The White House has grown increasingly concerned that Assad is preparing to use chemical weapons against his people after intelligence showed the movement of big stockpiles, including deadly sarin gas. Meanwhile, Turkey dispatched fighter jets after two strikes by Damascus on a Syrian town sent refugees and shrapnel across the Turkish border. NATO foreign ministers are expected to back the deployment of Patriot missile batteries to Turkey. House Republicans made a deficit-reduction offer that calls for $800 billion in increased tax revenue, half of what Obama proposed. Five European countries summoned their Israeli envoys to protest settlement plans in the wake of a U.N. vote on Palestinian status. Egypt's opposition plans mass protests against Morsi's moves to expand power, in the gravest threat to authority since Mubarak's ouster. Afghanistan's Karzai said he won't strike a security deal with the U.S. as long as it holds Afghan citizens. A bombing raid by Colombia's military killed at least 20 FARC rebels, a blow that will likely test peace talks. Dozens of oil pipelines buried beneath rivers nationwide could be at risk of rupturing due to flood erosion. Congolese troops returned to the city of Goma two days after rebels withdrew, but tensions there remained high. Vietnam said Chinese fishing boats cut cables of a Vietnamese ship, the latest incident in the South China Sea. A Chinese-controlled firm pleaded guilty to illegal export of coatings from the U.S. to a Pakistani nuclear plant. North Korea said the path of a rocket it plans to fire soon will be similar to one it planned for a failed April launch. Flu season has begun early, a sign that it could be more severe than in the past couple of years, health officials said. People with heart disease who followed healthy diets had a lower risk of repeat heart attacks, a study said. The pope will begin tweeting in eight languages, part of the church's effort to reach out to younger people. Email
